WEBVTT

0
00:00:03.339 --> 00:00:04.320
In 2011,

1
00:00:04.460 --> 00:00:07.150
we opened the black box and shared the blueprints,

2
00:00:07.500 --> 00:00:09.399
but blueprints don't build themselves.

3
00:00:10.100 --> 00:00:11.810
To actually change the industry,

4
00:00:12.069 --> 00:00:15.979
we needed an innovation engine that is powered by openness.

5
00:00:16.229 --> 00:00:18.069
What we needed was a community.

6
00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:19.469
Today,

7
00:00:19.559 --> 00:00:23.420
the open compute project isn't just a library of specifications.

8
00:00:24.549 --> 00:00:27.670
It's a living community driven by a shared goal,

9
00:00:27.909 --> 00:00:30.430
creating open solutions for data center

10
00:00:30.430 --> 00:00:33.930
operators facing extreme scaling challenges.

11
00:00:34.819 --> 00:00:37.400
Putting thousands of engineers in a single room

12
00:00:37.540 --> 00:00:39.330
gets you lots of great ideas,

13
00:00:39.580 --> 00:00:42.380
but that brainpower needs to be properly channeled.

14
00:00:43.150 --> 00:00:43.470
So,

15
00:00:43.630 --> 00:00:47.270
the work of OCP happens in specialized project groups.

16
00:00:48.290 --> 00:00:50.909
You can think of these as engineering departments.

17
00:00:51.560 --> 00:00:55.159
You have teams dedicated entirely to rec and power,

18
00:00:55.360 --> 00:00:57.470
other focused on cooling environments,

19
00:00:57.639 --> 00:01:00.700
and others write open source networking specifications,

20
00:01:00.959 --> 00:01:02.520
and so there are many more.

21
00:01:03.959 --> 00:01:06.169
But this is where the magic happens.

22
00:01:07.260 --> 00:01:09.800
We put the hyper scaler who actually

23
00:01:09.900 --> 00:01:12.360
builds and runs these mega data centers

24
00:01:12.540 --> 00:01:16.040
in the same room as the vendor who builds the hardware

25
00:01:16.180 --> 00:01:19.059
and the industry that is using that same equipment.

26
00:01:20.849 --> 00:01:22.599
They argue about physics.

27
00:01:22.849 --> 00:01:24.559
They iterate on the designs,

28
00:01:24.849 --> 00:01:29.550
and they solve problems together before a single piece of metal is stamped.

29
00:01:30.050 --> 00:01:31.489
But it's not the wild west.

30
00:01:31.849 --> 00:01:35.050
Before any design becomes an official OCP standard,

31
00:01:35.470 --> 00:01:38.319
it has to get past the technical gatekeepers,

32
00:01:38.489 --> 00:01:39.610
the steering committee.

33
00:01:40.540 --> 00:01:45.699
They are a panel of elected industry experts who ruthlessly review any submission.

34
00:01:46.730 --> 00:01:50.160
If a design doesn't meet the strict tenets for efficiency,

35
00:01:50.500 --> 00:01:51.000
impact,

36
00:01:51.139 --> 00:01:51.760
openness,

37
00:01:52.139 --> 00:01:53.199
scalability,

38
00:01:53.339 --> 00:01:54.599
and sustainability,

39
00:01:54.699 --> 00:01:57.040
it goes right back to the drawing board.

40
00:01:57.540 --> 00:02:00.330
But once the committee approves the specification,

41
00:02:00.500 --> 00:02:01.419
it's locked in.

42
00:02:01.620 --> 00:02:04.180
Vendors can then manufacture the physical hardware.

43
00:02:05.069 --> 00:02:07.540
Earned the OCP accepted mark.

44
00:02:08.169 --> 00:02:11.250
And lists them on the marketplace for the rest of the world to see,

45
00:02:11.449 --> 00:02:11.770
buy,

46
00:02:11.929 --> 00:02:12.649
and deploy.

47
00:02:13.839 --> 00:02:16.130
The community identifies the bottleneck,

48
00:02:16.399 --> 00:02:19.179
the project groups design the solution,

49
00:02:19.520 --> 00:02:21.580
and the committee ensures the quality.

50
00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:24.100
That's how we move the industry forward.

51
00:02:25.250 --> 00:02:27.580
And now that you know how the engine works,

52
00:02:27.940 --> 00:02:30.160
let's talk about my favorite topic,

53
00:02:30.660 --> 00:02:31.320
hardware.